Chi-Square Test of Independence: Fatal Injuries in the Iliad

Learning outcomes

  • Given a research question involving two categorical variables, construct the null and alternative hypotheses in words and using appropriate statistical symbols.

  • Describe and perform a chi-square test of independence for two categorical variables by:

    • Finding the expected counts
    • Calculating the \(X^2\) statistic

  • Interpret and evaluate a p-value for a chi-square test of independence for two categorical variables.

  • Use mathematical conditions to determine whether simulation-based methods or theory-based methods should be used when obtaining a p-value.

Fatal Injuries in the Iliad

Homerâs Iliad is an epic poem, compiled around 800 BCE, that describes several weeks of the last year of the 10-year siege of Troy (Ilion) by the Achaeans. The story centers on the rage of the great warrior Achilles. But it includes many details of injuries and outcomes, and is thus the oldest record of Greek medicine. The data report 146 recorded injuries for which both injury site and outcome are provided in the Iliad (Hutchinson, 2013).

For this activity we will focus on assessing if the location of an injury is associated with whether the injury was fatal.

Exploratory Data Analysis

  1. What is the explanatory variable?

The location of the injury

  1. What is the response variable?

The fatality of the injury

  1. What is the scope of inference for this study?

If the location of an injury is associated with fatality, for this sample of injuries from the battle of Troy. We can only infer onto the sample of injuries because the Iliad is not a random sample of all injuries from the battle of Troy. We can only infer an association between location site and injury because there was no random assignment of where someone was injured.

Visualizing the Data

To visualize the relationship between two categorical variables, we need to add some color into our previous bar plots. Letâs step through this process.

Last week, we started with a one variable bar plot that looked like this:

ggplot(data = iliad, 
       mapping = aes(x = `Injury Site`)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(x = "Location of Injury from Iliad", 
       y = "Number of Recorded Individuals")

The problem is, these bars donât show whether each injury included in the bar was fatal or nonfatal. To do this, we need to fill the bars with color, using the fill aesthetic.

In the code below, Iâve added a line that says fill = Lethal. This fills each bar with two colors, one for âFatalâ injuries and one for âNonfatalâ injuries.

ggplot(data = iliad, 
       mapping = aes(x = `Injury Site`, 
                     fill = Lethal)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(x = "Location of Injury from Iliad", 
       y = "Number of Recorded Individuals")

  1. How would you describe the orientation of this bar plot? Hint: The three choices are filled, stacked, and dodged.

This is a stacked bar plot, since the pink and blue bars are stacked on top of each other. It is not a filled bar plot since the frequencies are plotted on the y-axis not the proportions.

If we want a different layout for our bar plot than what geom_bar() does by default, we will need to be more specific! This is where the position option in geom_bar() comes in handy. There are three options for how the bars can be positioned:

  • "stack" (the default)
  • "dodge" (to put the bars side-by-side)
  • "fill" (to plot the proportions instead of frequencies)

Letâs change the code to use a dodge position instead of a stack position.

ggplot(data = iliad, 
       mapping = aes(x = `Injury Site`, 
                     fill = Lethal)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") + 
  labs(x = "Location of Injury from Iliad", 
       y = "Number of Recorded Individuals")

  1. Based on the plot does there appear to be an association between the variables? Explain your answer.

Yes, it appears that limb injuries are less fatal than the other locations.

Chi-Squared Test of Independence

Similar to what we did last week with one categorical variable, we will be performing a Chi-Squared test to compare what we saw in the data to what we would have expected to see if the null hypothesis was true.

  1. Write the null hypothesis for this study in words.

There is no association between the location of an injury and its fatality.

  1. Using the research question, write the alternative hypothesis in words.

There is an association between the location of an injury and its fatality â some injury locations are more / less fatal than others.

Expected Counts Under \(H_0\)

The Chi-Squared statistic (or \(X^2\)) has exactly the same formula to what we used last week. The only aspect that changes is how we get each cellâs expected count.

To find the expected count for each cell in our two variable table, we use three pieces of information:

  • the row total for that cell (denoted with an \(i\))
  • the column total for that cell (denoted with a \(j\))
  • the total sample size

We find the expected value of a cell using the following formula:

\[ \frac{\text{row}_i \text{ total} \times \text{column}_j \text{ total}}{\text{total sample size}} \]

Once we have each of these, we can create a table of what frequencies we would have expected to see if \(H_0\) was true.

  1. Iâve gotten you started with the expected value table. Fill out the remainder of the table below!
Lethal Body Head/neck Limb Unknown
Fatal \(\frac{155*67}{184} = 56.44\) \(\frac{155*45}{184} = 37.91\) \(\frac{155*34}{184} = 28.64\) \(\frac{155*38}{184} = 32.01\)
Nonfatal \(\frac{29*67}{184} = 10.56\) \(\frac{29*45}{184} = 7.09\) \(\frac{29*34}{184} = 5.36\) \(\frac{29*38}{184} = 5.99\)

Chi-Squared Statistic

Next, we compare each of our observed frequencies to what we would have expected if \(H_0\) was true. We compare how far âoffâ our observed frequencies are from what was expected in a very specific way, using the following calculation:

\[ \frac{(\text{observed} - \text{expected})^2}{\text{expected}} \]

  1. Using the formula above, calculate how far âoffâ each of the cells in our observed table is from what was expected under the null hypothesis. Hint: You should be adding up eight numbers for your \(X^2\) statistic!

\(\frac{(61 - 56.44)^2}{56.44} = 0.368\)

\(\frac{(44 - 37.91)^2}{37.91} = 0.978\)

\(\frac{(13 - 28.64)^2}{28.64} = 8.541\)

\(\frac{(37 - 32.01)^2}{32.01} = 0.778\)

\(\frac{(6 - 10.56)^2}{10.56} = 1.969\)

\(\frac{(1 - 7.09)^2}{7.09} = 5.231\)

\(\frac{(21 - 5.36)^2}{5.36} = 45.636\)

\(\frac{(1 - 5.99)^2}{5.99} = 4.157\)

  1. Adding all of these differences together to obtain our observed \(X^2\) statistic.

\(X^2 =\) \(0.368 + 0.978 + 8.541 + 0.778 + 1.969 + 5.231 + 45.636 + 4.157 = 67.658\)

Sampling Distribution of \(X^2\)

In order for us to calculate our p-valueâthe probability of observing an \(X^2\) statistic as or more extreme than what we got, if the null was trueâwe need a distribution of \(X^2\) statistics that could have happened if \(H_0\) was true.

Like all of our previous topics, there are two ways we can obtain this sampling distribution:

  • using mathematical theory
  • using computer simulation

Letâs see how each of these works!

Theory-based Null Distribution

For the Chi-Squared test of independence weâve been discussing, it can be mathematically shown that the distribution of \(X^2\) statistics follows a \(\chi^2\) distribution with \((r - 1) \times (c - 1)\) degrees of freedom, where \(r\) is the number of rows and \(c\) is the number of columns in the table. Keep in mind the total row and column donât count!

  1. How many degrees of freedom would be use for our \(\chi^2\) distribution?

\((2 - 1) \times (4 - 1) = 3\)

The \(\chi^2\) Distribution

Weâve seen the \(\chi^2\) distribution before in the context of the goodness-of-fit test. That is the same distribution we are using here! Recall, the \(\chi^2\) distribution has only positive values and the shape of the distribution is controlled by its degrees of freedom.

Conditions for Using a \(\chi^2\) Distribution

In order for the \(\chi^2\) distribution to be a good approximation of the true sampling distribution, we need to verify two conditions:

  • The observations are independent
  • We have a âlarge enoughâ sample size
    • This is checked by verifying there are at least 5 expected counts in each cell

If the condition about expected cell counts is violated, we are forced to use a simulation-based method.

  1. Are the conditions for using a \(\chi^2\) distribution to approximate the sampling distribution violated?

No! Every cell has more than 5 expected counts! The smallest expected count is the nonfatal limb injuries, which has an expected count of 5.36, so weâre good to go!

Using a \(\chi^2\) Distribution to Find the p-value

If we decided in #17 that it is not unreasonable for us to use the \(\chi^2\) distribution, then we can use R to find our p-value.

We will use the pchisq() function (which you saw last week). This function has three inputs:

  • the observed \(X^2\) statistic
  • how many degrees of freedom should be used for the \(\chi^2\) distribution
  • if the lower tail (left tail) should be used when calculating the p-value
  1. Using the values you calculated before, fill in the code below:
pchisq(67.658, df = 3, lower.tail = FALSE)

Running the code you just wrote in R gave me a p-value of approximately 0.

  1. Based on this p-value what conclusion would you reach regarding the null hypothesis? Hint: Go back and see what you wrote for your null and alternative hypotheses in #11 and #12!

With a p-value of approximately 0 we would reject the null (at any reasonable \(\alpha\)). This leads us to believe there is an association between the location of an injury and its fatality.

Simulated / Permuted Null Distribution

If the condition for expected counts is violated, we cannot use a \(\chi^2\) distribution to approximate what the true sampling distribution looks like. Instead, we need to use computer simulation to obtain our p-value.

Like all of the previous times, we can think about what the computer is doing using cards. Keep in mind, we are assuming the null hypothesis is true, which suggests there is no relationship between the location of someoneâs injury and whether they lived or died.

To carry out one simulation we need to do the following steps:

Step 1: Write the response (died / didnât die) and the location of the injury (body / head / limb / unknown) on 184 cards.

Step 2: Assume the null hypothesis is true and:

tear the cards in half, separating the injury location from the fatality

Step 3: Create a new dataset that could have happened if \(H_0\) was true by:

randomly pairing one location card with one fatality card until all 184 cards have a new pair.

Step 4: Create a new table of counts for the shuffled cards.

Keep in mind the column totals and the row totals will stay the same (there were only 34 people with limb injuries, and only 155 people who died). However, the cell values will change (we wonât always have 61 fatalities for body injuries).

Step 5: Calculate the \(X^2\) statistic for the simulation.

Because the row and column totals stay the same, the table of expected counts will be the same for every simulation! Thatâs handy!

Step 6: Plot the simulated \(X^2\) statistic on the distribution

Alright, after carrying out this process, I obtained the following distribution.

  1. Draw a line where the observed \(X^2\) statistic falls on this distribution.

  2. Estimate the p-value for testing if there is a relationship between the location of an injury and whether the individual survived.

There are zero simulated statistics as large or larger than our observed statistic of 67.658. Recall, since our \(X^2\) statistics are always positive, we only look at the right tail for our p-value. So, our p-value is less than 1/1000 or less than 0.001.

  1. Based on your p-value, what would you conclude for your null and alternative hypotheses? (Look back at what you said for #11 and #12)!

With a p-value of < 0.001 at an \(\alpha\) of 0.05, we would reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, we would conclude there is evidence of an association between the injury site and fatality.

  1. Did you reach similar conclusions using theory-based methods? Why do you believe that is the case?

We reached the same conclusion for both methods! This is because our condition of greater than 5 expected counts was not violated. If this condition was violated, using a \(\chi^2\) distribution to get our p-value would have been inappropriate and would have produced contradicting conclusions.
